                    </div>
                    <span>I believe that marriage is a fundamental right that should be available to all: regardless of gender!  There's too much hate and too much ignorance when it comes to a topic this critical.  This book is a must-own.  I 100% support same-sex marriage and we as a society should not settle for less!</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">The best book on gay marriage still falls short....</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>2</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>3</span>
                      /
                      <span>8</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-04-01</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>The same folks who argue that all human behavior is socially determined, are inclined to be the same folks who also insist that homosexuality is genetically determined.  Likewise, the same cosmpolitan urbanites who have been snickering at the traditional belief in the 'sanctity of marriage' are by and large the same people arguing for gay marriage.  The same people who have been snickering at "family values" of the traditional family unit are now demanding that being excluded from the legal defination of family is akin to racism.  It's no wonder that the overwhelming majority of Americans are finding the arguments on behalf of gay marriage tedious.  Rauch repeats the same contradictions when he argues out of both sides of his hat in this book. In one chapter, Rauch repeats the Andrew Sullivan argument that exclusion from the traditional committment of marriage would 'fix' the anti-social promiscuity of gay males. In the next chapter, he dismisses the concerns of traditionalists that the traditional family would be undermined by extending the protections of gay marriage to lesbians and gay males, who he argued are by nature promisicous and self destructive unless put under the restraint of the legal obligation of marriage.  Then in another chapter, he argues that marriage is just a legal contract devoid of any moral imperative or purpose whatsoever.  Take your pick, all of the arguments for gay marriage are in Rouch's book.  But to the public, the contraditions are obvious, which is why the gay marriage advocates are taking the tack of stuffing gay marriage down the public's throat via the courts system, instead of advocacy and local activism.  This is a book written by a gay marriage advocate for other gay marriage advocates.  It has nothing new or innovative to say. </span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Thoughtful, But...</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>1</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>6</span>
                      /
                      <span>21</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-01-31</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>...clearly an argument that displays first a loyalty to a specific outcome, and then seeks a way to get there.  
<br />
<br />Rauch does well not to demonize the opposition, who, certainly, can be their own worst enemies when it comes to debating the issue, trotting out canned phrases like "family values," and "the sanctity of marriage."  
<br />
<br />Nevertheless, his assertion that allowing gays to marry will strengthen the instution misses the point entirely.  First of all, he rightly recognizes that marriage is not just a religious institution, it is a social one.  By legalizing gay marriage--and even civil unions--you are forcing people not only to accept, but to endorse behavior that they find abnormal and morally abhorrent.  Like it or not, marriage is, by definition, the union of a man and a woman; it has never been anything else, until very recently in those mercifully few countries that have legalized it.  Dismissing this fact as a reactionary loyalty to tradition doesn't change it.  
<br />
<br />Gay marriage probably won't weak the instution of marriage as a whole--it is on shaky legs as it is--but it certainly won't help it.  The state regulates marriage as it is--we are NOT free to marry whomever we want, and just because we might want to badly, that doesn't make it our right.  It is government's job to protect the interests of its citizens, and clearly citizens feel they have a very strong interest in NOT redefining marriage.  And in fact, gays do have the same rights as the rest of us, contrary to what Mr. Rauch suggests.  Gays are free to marry a member of the opposite sex, within the boundaries set by law.  That they don't want to is hardly society's fault, and hardly a reason to change a fundamental social institution, just to satisfy their desires.
<br />
<br />His arguments that gay marriage is not a slippery slope remain unconvincing.  If objective values like tradition are so easily discarded to accomodate a small minority of malcontents, then what logical reasons can there be not to accomodate other malcontents? Does this mean that we can realistically expect people to petition to marry their dogs?  Of course not.  But is there really a compelling argument, then, for continuing to outlaw polygamy?  No.
<br />
<br />I agree with Rauch regarding leaving the argument to legislators rather than the judiciary.  Most Americans despise the idea of having a judiciary shove its values down our throats, and this more than anything is probably what has given traction to the anti's position.  As a matter of strategy, it's bad for gays; as a matter of policy, it's bad for America.
<br />
<br />
<br /></span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">some very good arguments</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
